AGI -&nbsp;Circa 60 thousand the faithful in St. Peter's Square who await the Easter message of Pope Francis and the subsequent blessing Urbi et Orbi from the Central Loggia of the Basilica. It makes known the Vatican press room.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Today we turn first of all our gaze towards the Holy City of Jerusalem, witness to the mystery of Jesus' passion, death and resurrection and to all Christian communities in the Holy Land. My thoughts go above all to the victims of the many conflicts that are ongoing in the world, beginning with those in Israel and Palestine, and in Ukraine."
&nbsp;
So Pope Francis in the Easter message before the blessing Urbi et Orbi. "Christ Risen open a way of peace for the marathon populations of those regions. As I invite respect for the principles of international law, I hope a general exchange of all prisoners between Russia and Ukraine: all for all!", the Pontiff stressed.
&nbsp;
<h2> Appeal for Gaza
"I appeal again to ensure that access to humanitarian aid in Gaza is guaranteed, urging once again to release the hostages abducted on 7 October and to an immediate ceasefire in the Strip." So Pope Francis in the Easter message before the blessing Urbi et Orbi.
&nbsp;
<h2> "War is always absurd and defeat" &nbsp;</h2>
"We do not allow the hostilities in place to continue to have serious repercussions on the civilian population, now exhausted, and especially on children. How much suffering we see in their eyes. they have forgotten to smile," "with their gaze they ask us: Why? Why? Why &nbsp; full destruction?" So Pope Francis in the Easter message before the blessing Urbi et Orbi.
&nbsp;
"War is always an absurdity and defeat! We do not leave that ever stronger winds of war on Europe and on the Mediterranean", the Pontiff emphasized. "Do not hide from the logic of weapons and rearmament. Peace never builds itself with weapons, but tending hands and opening hearts," he added.
